.TH XRANDR-PROFILE 1 "June 2026" "xrandr-profile VERSION" "General Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
xrandr-profile \- save and restore XRandR display profiles
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B xrandr-profile
.RB [ \-\-save
.IR profile ]
.RB [ \-\-load
.IR profile ]
.RB [ \-\-delete
.IR profile ]
.RB [ \-\-list ]
.RB [ \-\-list-all ]
.RB [ \-\-list-current ]
.RB [ \-\-watch ]
.RB [ \-\-names ]
.RB [ \-\-version ]
.RB [ \-\-help ]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B xrandr-profile
is a lightweight XRandR profile manager.

It saves and restores display configurations based on connected monitor
hardware using EDID matching, allowing layouts to be restored even when
monitors appear under different output names.

Profiles store monitor configuration properties including position,
resolution, refresh rate, rotation, reflection, panning, and scaling
transform.

.PP
When run without arguments,
.B xrandr-profile
automatically applies the most recently used profile matching the current
monitor configuration, if available.

.SH OPTIONS

.TP
.BI \-\-save " profile"
Save the current display configuration as
.IR profile .

.TP
.BI \-\-load " profile"
Load the specified
.IR profile .

.TP
.BI \-\-delete " profile"
Delete the specified
.IR profile .

.TP
.B \-\-list
List saved profiles matching the current monitor configuration.

.TP
.B \-\-list-all
List all saved profiles.

.TP
.B \-\-list-current
Print the current active display configuration.

.TP
.B \-\-watch
Applies the matching profile automatically when monitors are connected or disconnected.

.TP
.B \-\-names
Print only the name of the profiles.

.TP
.B \-\-version
Print version information and exit.

.TP
.B \-\-help
Display usage information and exit.

.SH FILES

.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/xrandr-profile/profiles
Default profile storage file.

.TP
.I ~/.config/xrandr-profile/profiles
Fallback profile storage file when
.B XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is unset.

.SH SIGNALS
The following apply only while running with
.BR \-\-watch .
.TP
.B SIGHUP
Force an immediate re-detection and re-apply. Useful after saving a new
profile with
.BR \-\-save .
.TP
.B SIGINT, SIGTERM
Exit cleanly.

.SH NOTES
.B \-\-watch
requires a running X session and should be started from within it, e.g. from
your window manager's autostart or a
.BR systemd (1)
user service. Run at most one watcher per session. While idle it blocks on
the X connection and consumes no CPU.

.SH EXAMPLES

.TP
Save the current layout:
.B xrandr-profile --save work

.TP
Restore a saved layout:
.B xrandr-profile --load docked

.TP
Automatically restore the last matching profile:
.B xrandr-profile

.TP
Watch for hotplug changes and auto-apply:
.B xrandr-profile --watch &

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR xrandr (1),
.BR X (7),
.BR autorandr (1)

